{"title_page": "David Moses Bridges", "text_new": "'''David Moses Bridges''' (May 17, 1962 - January 20, 2017) was a Native American environmentalist and artist known for his traditional birchbark canoes and baskets. He was a member of the Passamaquoddy tribal community on the [[Passamaquoddy Pleasant Point Reservation]]. Bridges fought for tribal environmental rights and was a co-founder of Mulankeyutmonen Nkihtakmikon<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/artists/david-moses-bridges|title=David Moses Bridges|website=First Peoples Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>, to preserve the [[Wabanaki Confederacy|Wabanaki]] culture.\n\nHe learned to build canoes from his great-grandfather Sylvester Gabriel and how to make baskets from his female relatives. \u00a0\n\n== Biography and education ==\nBridges was born in Portland, Maine, on May 17, 1962, and predominantly grew up with the Sipayik Native Community in South Portland. During the summertime, he spent most of his time with his grandfather Sylvester Gabriel. Bridges' family consisted of his parents, three siblings, and many relatives, most of whom were female. From his female relatives, he learned how to make baskets.\n\nAfter graduating high school in 1980, Bridges moved to San Francisco, California, where he lived for the next ten years. While living in San Francisco, he worked several jobs that included painting, carpeting, and group home counseling and was able to explore many different types of artwork. He would occasionally return home to work as a camp counselor. When he moved back home, Bridges's grandfather enlightened him on how to build canoes that were stable enough to go through rivers and bays smoothly. Bridges also took classes with Steve Cayard at the Woodenboat School in Brooklyn, Maine, and the two equally created workshops in Native and Anglo communities. He also took jobs at the Benjamin River and Brooklyn Boat Yard.\n\nIn 1993 Bridges and his wife Patricia Ayala Rocabado moved to Sipayik and decided to start a family. They would go on to have three children: Tobias, Sabattus, and Natanis. When his first son was four, Bridges began studying history at the University of Maine at Machias, after which point he moved to Bethel, Maine. Bridges held birch canoe workshops and together with his wife, held presentations at several anthropological, and archaeological conferences in North and South America. He also held presentations at universities and cultural institutions.\n\nWhen Bridges was 54, he was diagnosed with [[Paranasal sinuses|sinus cancer]], which led to his death on January 20, 2017. His most capable eldest son, Tobias, continued his work by joining the canoe project led by Cayard and Patricia, further pursuing her parent's careers in [[indigenous archaeology]]. Patricia also began working on an art book and a film on Bridges.\n\n== Early life ==\nDavid Moses Bridges was born on May 17, 1962. He mainly spent the majority of his childhood in the South of Portland, Maine. Bridges grew up with his father Earl Bridges, mother Hilda Lewis,  <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://obituaries.bangordailynews.com/obituary/david-bridges-867651212/|title=Remembering the life of David Bridges 1962 - 2017|website=obituaries.bangordailynews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>  his great-grandfather, Sylvester Gabriel, and his sister. Bridges' great-grandfather lived with them as a care-take for Bridges and his sister.\n\nGrowing up, Bridges attended many camps that were related to his tribal community. Bridges fell in love with the camp so much that when he got older he would come home from San Francisco to Portland during the summer to become a camp counselor.\n\nBridges' great-grandfather introduced Bridges to the birchbark canoe. Due to his great-grandfather's old age, they were not able to create a birchbark canoe together. Bridges' great-grandfather passed away in 1972 when Bridges was 10 years old but he left Bridges with tools such as a crooked knife, draw knife, and an awl<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://asongbird.com/david-moses-bridges-the-trees-let-me-know/|title=David Moses Bridges \u2013 The Trees Let Me Know {{!}} Abena Songbird|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>.\n\nEver since then, Bridges had the heart to finish the canoe so he attended school and studied more about the traditions related to his tribal community and about boat making.\n\nBridges started making birchbark canoes to preserve the dying tradition. Bridges made canoes with his students, who were of all ages. He also went to Universities and Museums giving presentations about his work. \n\n== Artworks ==\n\n=== Traditional birchbark canoe ===\n[[File:Birchbark_canoe,_Abbe_Museum,_Bar_Harbor,_ME_IMG_2301.JPG|thumb|Traditional Birchbark Canoe. This canoe is at the Abbe Museum, Bar Harbor. David Moses Bridges brought back the traditional birchbark canoe to show people that their Reservation did not disappear.]]\nBridge\u2019s ancestors started off making the traditional [[Birch bark|birchbark]] canoe until his great father\u2019s time. His grandfather gave him the tools and the materials to create a canoe. Bridges was inspired to build the birchbark canoes because he believed that it would help keep the tradition alive in the modern-day and wanted people to thank their ancestors for creating this masterpiece.<ref>{{Citation|title=David Moses Bridges - Birchbark Canoes|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WHd8z4bEHUA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> The traditional birchbark canoe had to be thin so that it was easy to carry after using it. The material needed to create the birchbark canoe was birchbark and spruce roots<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jumaka.com/birchbarkcanoe/materialspage/roots.htm|title=Building a Birchbark Canoe - Materials - Spruce roots|website=jumaka.com|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>. According to Bridges, no special tools were needed except a crooked knife made out of beaver tooth<ref>{{Citation|title=David Moses Bridges - Birchbark Canoes|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WHd8z4bEHUA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>.\n\n=== Birchbark box ===\nThe birchbark box was made out of birch bark and spruce root. Bridges died before he could complete the box. He did not intend to fully decorate the birchbark box, as he wanted people to see and appreciate the beauty of the bark itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abbemuseum.org/blog/tag/David+Moses+Bridges|title=David Moses Bridges \u2014 Blog|website=Abbe Museum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Story Basket\" ===\nBridges made this basket while experiencing family difficulties and reflects his internal struggles to provide for his family.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mainememory.net/sitebuilder/site/2950/page/4637/display|title=\"Story Basket\" by Passamaquoddy artist David Moses Bridges|website=My Maine Stories|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abbemuseum.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/B0708F95-D7EF-480A-8EE0-465587151783|title=Box|website=abbemuseum.pastperfectonline.com|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> It features several scenes, one of which is of his pregnant wife and child Sabattus asking for food.<ref name=\":0\" />  Another features Bridges hunting for moose and carrying a canoe, as well as Tobias alone pulling a sled. Behind all of these scenes, an ancestor is shown watching over the family.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== [[Sheath knife|Knife sheath]] ===\nBridges created this knife sheath while working on other artwork. He would often carry his knife around and as he did not want to cut himself on the sharp edge, he created a sheath using birch bark and spruce roots, materials with which he was already working.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abbemuseum.org/blog/tag/David+Moses+Bridges|title=David Moses Bridges \u2014 Blog|website=Abbe Museum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibition ==\n[[Abbe Museum]] located in Bar Harbor, Maine\n\nPeabody Essex Museum located in Salem, Massachusetts. September 27, 2014 ~ September 20, 2015\n\nHeard Museum Guild Indian Fair and Market, 2015 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsmaven.io/indiancountrytoday/archive/david-moses-bridges-an-artist-and-activist-walks-on-35MepFbVg0CHOSL82BT71w|title=David Moses Bridges: An Artist and Activist Walks On|website=Maven|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n'''Solo Exhibitions:'''\n\nOnly Connect: Richard vanBuren & David Moses Bridges, Aucocisco Gallery, Portland, Maine. January 15, 2008 ~ March 1, 2008 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mutualart.com/Artist/David-Moses-Bridges/39DF118F55923CC4/Biography|title=Bridges, David Moses {{!}} Biography|website=www.mutualart.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n'''Group Exhibitions''':\n\n* Wabanaki Antiques Expo, May 9 \u00a0\n* Branching Out: Trees as Art, Peabody Essex Museum, Salem, Massachusetts ~2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mutualart.com/Artist/David-Moses-Bridges/39DF118F55923CC4/Biography|title=Bridges, David Moses {{!}} Biography|website=www.mutualart.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n* Maine Indian Basketry Exhibition, at Maine Fiberarts. This exhibition included Pam Cunningham, George Neptune, Clara Keezer, Molly Neptune Parker, Jeremy Frey, Fred Tomah, Mart Sanipass, Thersea Secord, and Sarah Sochbeson. May 5 ~June 30, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.midcoastmaine.com/calendar/event/7210|title=Maine Indian Basketry Exhibition - June 22, 2015 - Southern Midcoast Maine Chamber|website=www.midcoastmaine.com|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\n- [[Eiteljorg Museum of American Indians and Western Art|Eitelijorg]]  (Indianapolis, IN)\n\n- Downeast Heritage Museum (Calais, ME)\n\n- Penobscot Marine Museum (Searsport, ME)\n\n- Abbe Museum (Bar Harbor, ME)\n\n- Hudson Museum (Orono, ME)\n\n- Passamaquoddy Cultural Heritage Museum (Indian Township, ME)\n\n- National Museum of the American Indian (New York, NY)\n\n*\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\n* Main Arts Commissions gave him the name Traditional Arts Fellow, highest honor in craft<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2017/01/23/passamaquoddy-canoe-maker-david-moses-bridges-dies-at-54/|title=Passamaquoddy canoe maker and craftsman David Moses Bridges dies at 54|last=KeyesPortl|first=Bob|last2=Herald|first2=Press|date=2017-01-23|website=Kennebec Journal and Morning Sentinel|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n* 1997; Patrick Miranda Foundation\n* 1998; Patrick Miranda Foundation\n* 2000; Maine Arts Commission, Master/Apprentice Award\n* 2004; Maine Boats and Harbors, Boat of the Year Award\n* 2005; First Peoples Fund, Community Spirit Award\n* 2006; First People\u2019s Fund gave him its Community Spirit Award, National Honor in recognition of his work<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2017/01/23/passamaquoddy-canoe-maker-david-moses-bridges-dies-at-54/|title=Passamaquoddy canoe maker and craftsman David Moses Bridges dies at 54|last=KeyesPortl|first=Bob|last2=Herald|first2=Press|date=2017-01-23|website=Kennebec Journal and Morning Sentinel|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n* 2007; Jennifer Easton Community Spirit Award honoree\n* 2007; Fund for Folklife Culture, Professional Development Grant\n* 2007; First Peoples Fund, Cultural Capitol Fellow\n* 2008; Artists in Business Leadership Fellow, Cultural Capital Fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/artists/david-moses-bridges|title=David Moses Bridges|website=First Peoples Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n* 2008; Eitelijorg Museum, Artist and Residence Fellowship\n* 2008; New England Foundation for the Arts\n* 2014; Santa Fe Indian Market, Honorable Mention\n* 2015; Heard Museum Indian Fair and Market, Basket Division, First place\n* 2017; letter of tribute from members of the Senate and House of Representatiave of the State of Maine\n\n== Legacy ==\nAfter Bridges's death his wife, Patricia Ayala Rocabado, created an artbook of his works. A documentary on his life, ''Rhythms of the Heart'', was created by Thom Willey and released in August 2017. In 2019 authors Donald Soctomah and Jean Flahive released ''The Canoe Maker: David Moses Bridges, Passamaquoddy Birch Bark Artisan'' through Custom Museum Publishing LLC.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flahive, Jean,|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1119722836|title=The canoe maker David Moses Bridges, Passamaquoddy birch bark artisan / Jean Flahive and Donald Soctomah; illustrated by Mari Dieumegard.|others=Donald, Soctomah,, Mari, Dieumegard,|isbn=978-1-63381-171-3|location=Thomaston, Me.|oclc=1119722836}}</ref>\n\nA scholarship has been named after Bridges, the David Moses Bridges Scholarship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/news/rembembering-david-moses-bridges|title=REMEMBERING DAVID MOSES BRIDGES|website=First Peoples Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>, which is granted by the First Peoples Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/news/rembembering-david-moses-bridges|title=REMEMBERING DAVID MOSES BRIDGES|website=First Peoples Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> David Moses Bridges scholarship was provided though the Main Community Foundation that supports the First People Fund Cultural<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/news/rembembering-david-moses-bridges|title=REMEMBERING DAVID MOSES BRIDGES|website=First Peoples Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>. \n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{officialwebsite|https://davidmosesbridges.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bridges, David Moses}}\n[[Category:Native American people]]\n", "text_old": "'''David Moses Bridges''' (May 17, 1962 - January 20, 2017) was a Native American environmentalist and artist known for his traditional birchbark canoes and baskets. He was a member of the Passamaquoddy tribal community on the [[Passamaquoddy Pleasant Point Reservation]]. Bridges fought for tribal environmental rights and was a co-founder of Mulankeyutmonen Nkihtakmikon<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpeoplesfund.org/artists/david-moses-bridges|title=David Moses Bridges|website=First Peoples Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>, to preserve the [[Wabanaki Confederacy|Wabanaki]] culture.\n\nHe learned to build canoes from his great-grandfather Sylvester Gabriel and how to make baskets from his female relatives. \u00a0\n\n== Biography and education ==\nBridges was born in Portland, Maine, on May 17, 1962, and predominantly grew up with the Sipayik Native Community in South Portland. During the summertime, he spent most of his time with his grandfather Sylvester Gabriel. Bridges' family consisted of his parents, three siblings, and many relatives, most of whom were female. From his female relatives, he learned how to make baskets.\n\nAfter graduating high school in 1980, Bridges moved to San Francisco, California, where he lived for the next ten years. While living in San Francisco, he worked several jobs that included painting, carpeting, and group home counseling and was able to explore many different types of artwork. He would occasionally return home to work as a camp counselor. When he moved back home, Bridges's grandfather enlightened him on how to build canoes that were stable enough to go through rivers and bays smoothly. Bridges also took classes with Steve Cayard at the Woodenboat School in Brooklyn, Maine, and the two equally created workshops in Native and Anglo communities. He also took jobs at the Benjamin River and Brooklyn Boat Yard.\n\nIn 1993 Bridges and his wife Patricia Ayala Rocabado moved to Sipayik and decided to start a family. They would go on to have three children: Tobias, Sabattus, and Natanis. When his first son was four, Bridges began studying history at the University of Maine at Machias, after which point he moved to Bethel, Maine. Bridges held birch canoe workshops and together with his wife, held presentations at several anthropological, and archaeological conferences in North and South America. He also held presentations at universities and cultural institutions.\n\nWhen Bridges was 54, he was diagnosed with [[Paranasal sinuses|sinus cancer]], which led to his death on January 20, 2017. His most capable eldest son, Tobias, continued his work by joining the canoe project led by Cayard and Patricia, further pursuing her parent's careers in [[indigenous archaeology]]. Patricia also began working on an art book and a film on Bridges.\n\n== Early life ==\nDavid Moses Bridges was born on May 17, 1962. He mainly spent the majority of his childhood in the South of Portland, Maine. Bridges grew up with his father Earl Bridges, mother Hilda Lewis,  <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://obituaries.bangordailynews.com/obituary/david-bridges-867651212/|title=Remembering the life of David Bridges 1962 - 2017|website=obituaries.bangordailynews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>  his great-grandfather, Sylvester Gabriel, and his sister. Bridges' great-grandfather lived with them as a care-take for Bridges and his sister.\n\nGrowing up, Bridges attended many camps that were related to his tribal community. Bridges fell in love with the camp so much that when he got older he would come home from San Francisco to Portland during the summer to become a camp counselor.\n\nBridges' great-grandfather introduced Bridges to the birchbark canoe. Due to his great-grandfather's old age, they were not able to create a birchbark canoe together. Bridges' great-grandfather passed away in 1972 when Bridges was 10 years old but he left Bridges with tools such as a crooked knife, draw knife, and an awl<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://asongbird.com/david-moses-bridges-the-trees-let-me-know/|title=David Moses Bridges \u2013 The Trees Let Me Know {{!}} Abena Songbird|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>.\n\nEver since then, Bridges had the heart to finish the canoe so he attended school and studied more about the traditions related to his tribal community and about boat making.\n\nBridges started making birchbark canoes to preserve the dying tradition. Bridges made canoes with his students, who were of all ages. He also went to Universities and Museums giving presentations about his work. \n\n== Artworks ==\n\n=== Traditional birchbark canoe ===\n[[File:Birchbark_canoe,_Abbe_Museum,_Bar_Harbor,_ME_IMG_2301.JPG|thumb|Traditional Birchbark Canoe. This canoe is at the Abbe Museum, Bar Harbor. David Moses Bridges brought back the traditional birchbark canoe to show people that their Reservation did not disappear.]]\nBridge\u2019s ancestors started off making the traditional [[Birch bark|birchbark]] canoe until his great father\u2019s time. His grandfather gave him the tools and the materials to create a canoe. Bridges was inspired to build the birchbark canoes because he believed that it would help keep the tradition alive in the modern-day and wanted people to thank their ancestors for creating this masterpiece.<ref>{{Citation|title=David Moses Bridges - Birchbark Canoes|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WHd8z4bEHUA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> The traditional birchbark canoe had to be thin so that it was easy to carry after using it. The material needed to create the birchbark canoe was birchbark and spruce roots<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jumaka.com/birchbarkcanoe/materialspage/roots.htm|title=Building a Birchbark Canoe - Materials - Spruce roots|website=jumaka.com|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>. According to Bridges, no special tools were needed except a crooked knife made out of beaver tooth<ref>{{Citation|title=David Moses Bridges - Birchbark Canoes|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WHd8z4bEHUA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>.\n\n=== Birchbark Box ===\nThe birchbark box was made out of birch bark and spruce root. Bridges died before he could complete the box. He did not intend to fully decorate the birchbark box, as he wanted people to see and appreciate the beauty of the bark itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abbemuseum.org/blog/tag/David+Moses+Bridges|title=David Moses Bridges \u2014 Blog|website=Abbe Museum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n=== \"Story Basket\" ===\nBridges made this basket while experiencing family difficulties and reflects his internal struggles to provide for his family.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mainememory.net/sitebuilder/site/2950/page/4637/display|title=\"Story Basket\" by Passamaquoddy artist David Moses Bridges|website=My Maine Stories|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abbemuseum.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/B0708F95-D7EF-480A-8EE0-465587151783|title=Box|website=abbemuseum.pastperfectonline.com|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> It features several scenes, one of which is of his pregnant wife and child Sabattus asking for food.<ref name=\":0\" />  Another features Bridges hunting for moose and carrying a canoe, as well as Tobias alone pulling a sled. Behind all of these scenes, an ancestor is shown watching over the family.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== [[Sheath knife|Knife sheath]] ===\nBridges created this knife sheath while working on other artwork. He would often carry his knife around and as he did not want to cut himself on the sharp edge, he created a sheath using birch bark and spruce roots, materials with which he was already working.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abbemuseum.org/blog/tag/David+Moses+Bridges|title=David Moses Bridges \u2014 Blog|website=Abbe Museum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibition ==\n[[Abbe Museum]] located in Bar Harbor, Maine\n\nPeabody Essex Museum located in Salem, Massachusetts. September 27, 2014 ~ September 20, 2015\n\nHeard Museum Guild Indian Fair and Market, 2015 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsmaven.io/indiancountrytoday/archive/david-moses-bridges-an-artist-and-activist-walks-on-35MepFbVg0CHOSL82BT71w|t